</head>
<body>
    <canvas id="universeCanvas"></canvas>
    <div id="ui-overlay">
        <div class="title">Recursive Cosmos</div>
        <div>[SCROLL] to zoom</div>
        <div>[DRAG] to pan</div>
        <div id="zoom-level">Zoom: 1.00</div>
        <div id="coords">Pos: (0, 0)</div>
    </div>

    <script>
    /*
    ==================================================================================================
    STRATEGIC EXECUTION FRAMEWORK: Sub-strategy 3 - Hierarchical Grammar & Modular Composition
    ==================================================================================================
    This script is the complete and rigorous execution of the assigned sub-strategy. It constructs a
    procedurally generated universe within a single, standalone HTML file.

    I. STRATEGY RESTATEMENT:
    The core approach is to define the universe using a formal grammar (L-system). This grammar dictates
    the hierarchical placement of generative modules (e.g., galaxies, star systems). 'Infinity' is
    achieved via the combinatorial expansion of the grammar, and the aesthetic is curated through the
    design of the modules and the grammar rules.

    II. EXECUTION PLAN:
    The implementation is structured to directly map to the tactical objectives and execution
    methodology outlined in the sub-strategy.

    1.  AESTHETIC AXIOM & MODULE LIBRARY (Tactical Objective 1):
        - A "library of parametric generative modules" is implemented as JavaScript functions
          (`drawGalaxy`, `drawStarSystem`, etc.).
        - These functions take a seed and other parameters to generate visual representations on the canvas.
        - The aesthetic is defined by color palettes, particle effects (glow), and composition rules.

    2.  FORMAL GRAMMAR DEFINITION (Tactical Objective 2):
        - A JavaScript object (`GRAMMAR_RULES`) serves as the formal grammar.
        - The keys are non-terminal symbols (e.g., 'U' for Universe), and the values are possible
          expansion rules.
        - This defines the spatial and probabilistic relationships between celestial objects.

    3.  ON-DEMAND GENERATION ENGINE (Tactical Objective 3):
        - A Quadtree data structure (`Quadtree` class) is implemented from first principles. This
          structure partitions the 2D space.
        - The engine, embodied in the `populateNode` and `update` methods of the Quadtree, evaluates
          the grammar 'on-demand'. A node is only subdivided and populated with content (by applying
          a grammar rule) when the user's view requires that level of detail.
        - This is the "Cosmological Generation Engine" parsing rules based on user location (view).

    4.  LOD SYSTEM & INTERACTION (Tactical Objective 4):
        - The Level of Detail (LOD) system is integrated directly into the module drawing functions.
        - Based on the current zoom level, a function will render a simplified 'impostor' (e.g., a
          single bright pixel for a distant galaxy) or the fully generated module (e.g., a spiral of
          stars).
        - This creates a structured transition between scales, directly corresponding to the
          grammatical hierarchy.

    III. KNOWLEDGE INTEGRATION:
    The Knowledge Packet is currently empty. Therefore, this execution proceeds based solely on the
    provided sub-strategy without external hypotheses.

    IV. ANALYTICAL FRAMEWORK & TERMINOLOGY:
    - `Canvas`: The rendering surface.
    - `View`: An object representing the user's camera (position and zoom).
    - `Quadtree`: The spatial partitioning data structure.
    - `Grammar`: The rule-set for procedural generation.
    - `Module`: A function that generates a specific celestial object.
    - `Seed`: A number used to initialize a pseudo-random number generator for deterministic generation.
    - `PRNG`: Pseudo-Random Number Generator. A simple LCG is implemented to ensure deterministic,
               seedable randomness, avoiding the non-seedable `Math.random()`.
    - All mathematical operations, data structures, and algorithms are derived from first principles
      within this script, in adherence to the absolute prohibition of assumptions.
    ==================================================================================================
    */

    // SECTION 1: CORE SYSTEMS AND UTILITIES
    // This section establishes the foundational components required by the generation engine.

    // 1.1: Canvas and Rendering Context Setup
    const canvas = document.getElementById('universeCanvas');
    const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');

    // Set canvas dimensions to fill the viewport
    let width = window.innerWidth;
    let height = window.innerHeight;
    canvas.width = width;
    canvas.height = height;

    window.addEventListener('resize', () => {
        width = window.innerWidth;
        height = window.innerHeight;
        canvas.width = width;
        canvas.height = height;
    });

    // 1.2: Seedable Pseudo-Random Number Generator (PRNG)
    // JUSTIFICATION: The sub-strategy requires a generative system. Deterministic generation is
    // crucial for a consistent universe that can be explored. Standard `Math.random()` is not seedable.
    // Therefore, a Linear Congruential Generator (LCG) is implemented from first principles.
    // LCG formula: X_{n+1} = (a * X_n + c) mod m
    class LCG {
        constructor(seed) {
            // Parameters are chosen for their common use and decent properties.
            this.m = 2**32; // Modulus
            this.a = 1664525; // Multiplier
            this.c = 1013904223; // Increment
            // The seed is the initial state. Ensure it is an integer.
            this.state = Math.floor(seed);
        }

        // Returns a pseudo-random integer
        nextInt() {
            this.state = (this.a * this.state + this.c) % this.m;
            return this.state;
        }

        // Returns a pseudo-random float between 0 (inclusive) and 1 (exclusive)
        nextFloat() {
            return this.nextInt() / this.m;
        }
    }

    // 1.3: View and Interaction State
    // JUSTIFICATION: This object manages the user's viewport (camera) into the universe.
    // It is manipulated by user input to achieve the 'infinite zoom' and panning effects.
    const view = {
        x: 0,
        y: 0,
        zoom: 1.0,
        targetZoom: 1.0,
        targetX: 0,
        targetY: 0
    };

    // Mouse state for panning
    let isDragging = false;
    let lastMouseX = 0;
    let lastMouseY = 0;

    canvas.addEventListener('mousedown', (e) => {
        isDragging = true;
        lastMouseX = e.clientX;
        lastMouseY = e.clientY;
    });

    canvas.addEventListener('mouseup', () => {
        isDragging = false;
    });

    canvas.addEventListener('mouseleave', () => {
        isDragging = false;
    });

    canvas.addEventListener('mousemove', (e) => {
        if (isDragging) {
            const dx = e.clientX - lastMouseX;
            const dy = e.clientY - lastMouseY;
            // Panning speed should be inversely proportional to zoom
            view.targetX -= dx / view.zoom;
            view.targetY -= dy / view.zoom;
            lastMouseX = e.clientX;
            lastMouseY = e.clientY;
        }
    });

    canvas.addEventListener('wheel', (e) => {
        e.preventDefault();
        const zoomFactor = 1.1;
        const mouseX = e.clientX;
        const mouseY = e.clientY;

        // Convert mouse screen coordinates to world coordinates
        const worldX = (mouseX - width / 2) / view.zoom + view.x;
        const worldY = (mouseY - height / 2) / view.zoom + view.y;

        if (e.deltaY < 0) { // Zoom in
            view.targetZoom *= zoomFactor;
        } else { // Zoom out
            view.targetZoom /= zoomFactor;
        }

        // Ensure zoom stays within reasonable bounds to prevent floating point issues.
        view.targetZoom = Math.max(1e-10, Math.min(1e10, view.targetZoom));

        // Adjust target position to zoom towards the cursor
        const newWorldX = (mouseX - width / 2) / view.targetZoom + view.targetX;
        const newWorldY = (mouseY - height / 2) / view.targetZoom + view.targetY;

        view.targetX += worldX - newWorldX;
        view.targetY += worldY - newWorldY;
    });


    // SECTION 2: THE HIERARCHICAL GRAMMAR
    // STRATEGIC JUSTIFICATION: This section implements the core of "Sub-strategy 3". A formal
    // grammar defines the structure of the universe, allowing for complex, hierarchical, and
    // aesthetically controlled procedural generation.

    const GRAMMAR_RULES = {
        // Each rule is an array of possible expansions.
        // Each expansion is an object with a 'structure' string and a 'weight' for probabilistic selection.
        // Symbols:
        // U: Universe (Root)
        // C: Galaxy Cluster
        // V: Void
        // G: Galaxy
        // N: Nebula
        // S: Star System
        // E: Empty Space

        // The root symbol 'U' expands into a grid of clusters and voids.
        'U': [{ weight: 1.0, structure: 'CVCVCVCVC' }],

        // A 'C' (Cluster) expands into a grid containing galaxies and nebulae.
        'C': [{ weight: 0.8, structure: 'GEGENGEGE' }, { weight: 0.2, structure: 'GGNVGEGNG' }],

        // A 'V' (Void) is mostly empty but has a small chance of containing a lone galaxy.
        'V': [{ weight: 0.9, structure: 'EEEEEEEEE' }, { weight: 0.1, structure: 'EEEEGEEEE' }],

        // A 'G' (Galaxy) expands into star systems and empty patches.
        'G': [{ weight: 1.0, structure: 'SESESESES' }],

        // A 'N' (Nebula) also contains star systems, but perhaps more sparsely.
        'N': [{ weight: 1.0, structure: 'ESEEESEEE' }],

        // 'S' (Star System) and 'E' (Empty) are terminal symbols for this grammar's depth.
        // The drawing modules will handle their specific generation.
        'S': [],
        'E': [],
    };

    // This function selects a rule expansion based on weighted probability.
    function expandSymbol(symbol, rng) {
        const rules = GRAMMAR_RULES[symbol];
        if (!rules || rules.length === 0) {
            return null; // Terminal symbol
        }

        const totalWeight = rules.reduce((sum, rule) => sum + rule.weight, 0);
        let random = rng.nextFloat() * totalWeight;

        for (const rule of rules) {
            if (random < rule.weight) {
                return rule.structure;
            }
            random -= rule.weight;
        }
        return rules[rules.length - 1].structure; // Fallback
    }

    // SECTION 3: MODULAR GENERATION & RENDERING
    // STRATEGIC JUSTIFICATION: This section implements the "library of parametric generative modules"
    // and the LOD system. Each function is responsible for drawing a celestial object, with its
    // appearance determined by a seed and its level of detail determined by the current zoom.

    // 3.1: Base Particle Drawing Function
    function drawGlowParticle(ctx, x, y, radius, color, glowColor) {
        ctx.save();
        ctx.globalCompositeOperation = 'lighter'; // Additive blending for a glow effect

        const grad = ctx.createRadialGradient(x, y, 0, x, y, radius);
        grad.addColorStop(0, `rgba(${color.r}, ${color.g}, ${color.b}, 1)`);
        grad.addColorStop(0.4, `rgba(${glowColor.r}, ${glowColor.g}, ${glowColor.b}, 0.5)`);
        grad.addColorStop(1, `rgba(${glowColor.r}, ${glowColor.g}, ${glowColor.b}, 0)`);

        ctx.fillStyle = grad;
        ctx.beginPath();
        ctx.arc(x, y, radius, 0, Math.PI * 2);
        ctx.fill();

        ctx.restore();
    }

    // 3.2: Module - Star System
    function drawStarSystem(ctx, seed, cx, cy, size, zoom) {
        const rng = new LCG(seed);
        const starType = rng.nextFloat();

        let starColor, glowColor;
        if (starType < 0.1) { // Blue Giant
            starColor = { r: 170, g: 190, b: 255 };
            glowColor = { r: 100, g: 120, b: 200 };
        } else if (starType < 0.8) { // Yellow Dwarf
            starColor = { r: 255, g: 255, b: 200 };
            glowColor = { r: 200, g: 200, b: 100 };
        } else { // Red Dwarf
            starColor = { r: 255, g: 180, b: 120 };
            glowColor = { r: 200, g: 100, b: 50 };
        }

        const radius = Math.max(0.5, size * 0.05); // Radius in pixels
        drawGlowParticle(ctx, cx, cy, radius, starColor, glowColor);

        // LOD: Draw planets only when zoomed in sufficiently
        const planetLOD = 0.01;
        if (size > width * planetLOD) {
            const numPlanets = Math.floor(rng.nextFloat() * 10);
            for (let i = 0; i < numPlanets; i++) {
                const angle = rng.nextFloat() * Math.PI * 2;
                const dist = (rng.nextFloat() * 0.4 + 0.1) * size;
                const planetX = cx + Math.cos(angle) * dist;
                const planetY = cy + Math.sin(angle) * dist;
                const planetRadius = Math.max(0.5, size * 0.005);

                ctx.fillStyle = `rgba(150, 150, 150, 0.8)`;
                ctx.beginPath();
                ctx.arc(planetX, planetY, planetRadius, 0, Math.PI * 2);
                ctx.fill();
            }
        }
    }

    // 3.3: Module - Galaxy
    function drawGalaxy(ctx, seed, cx, cy, size, zoom) {
        // LOD Impostor: If galaxy is small on screen, draw a single bright particle.
        const impostorLOD = 0.05;
        if (size < width * impostorLOD) {
            drawGlowParticle(ctx, cx, cy, Math.max(1, size * 0.01), {r:200, g:200, b:255}, {r:150, g:150, b:255});
            return;
        }

        const rng = new LCG(seed);
        const numArms = 2 + Math.floor(rng.nextFloat() * 4);
        const armSpread = rng.nextFloat() * 0.5 + 0.5;
        const starCount = 500; // Constant for performance, but could be seeded

        for (let i = 0; i < starCount; i++) {
            const angle = rng.nextFloat() * Math.PI * 2 * numArms;
            const dist = rng.nextFloat() * (size / 2);

            const spiralAngle = angle * armSpread + dist / (size/2) * 5;

            const starX = cx + Math.cos(spiralAngle) * dist;
            const starY = cy + Math.sin(spiralAngle) * dist;

            const starBrightness = 150 + Math.floor(rng.nextFloat() * 105);
            ctx.fillStyle = `rgb(${starBrightness}, ${starBrightness}, ${starBrightness})`;
            ctx.fillRect(starX, starY, 1, 1);
        }
    }

    // 3.4: Module - Nebula
    function drawNebula(ctx, seed, cx, cy, size, zoom) {
        // LOD Impostor
        if (size < width * 0.02) {
            ctx.fillStyle = `rgba(100, 50, 150, 0.3)`;
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.arc(cx, cy, size/2, 0, Math.PI * 2);
            ctx.fill();
            return;
        }

        const rng = new LCG(seed);
        const numClouds = 20;
        ctx.save();
        ctx.globalCompositeOperation = 'lighter';
        for (let i = 0; i < numClouds; i++) {
            const x = cx + (rng.nextFloat() - 0.5) * size;
            const y = cy + (rng.nextFloat() - 0.5) * size;
            const radius = rng.nextFloat() * size * 0.3;

            const grad = ctx.createRadialGradient(x, y, 0, x, y, radius);
            const r = 50 + rng.nextFloat() * 100;
            const g = 20 + rng.nextFloat() * 50;
            const b = 80 + rng.nextFloat() * 120;
            grad.addColorStop(0, `rgba(${r}, ${g}, ${b}, 0.2)`);
            grad.addColorStop(1, `rgba(${r}, ${g}, ${b}, 0)`);

            ctx.fillStyle = grad;
            ctx.fillRect(x - radius, y - radius, radius * 2, radius * 2);
        }
        ctx.restore();
    }


    // SECTION 4: ON-DEMAND GENERATION ENGINE (QUADTREE)
    // STRATEGIC JUSTIFICATION: This Quadtree implementation is the heart of the on-demand generation
    // engine. It recursively subdivides space, applying grammar rules to populate newly created
    // regions only when they become visible, thus creating the illusion of an infinite universe.

    const MAX_QUADTREE_DEPTH = 10;
    const MIN_NODE_SIZE_ON_SCREEN = 50; // pixels

    class Quadtree {
        constructor(x, y, size, depth, symbol) {
            this.x = x;
            this.y = y;
            this.size = size;
            this.depth = depth;
            this.symbol = symbol; // Symbol from the grammar
            this.children = null; // To hold four child Quadtrees
            this.isPopulated = false; // Tracks if grammar has been applied
            this.seed = this.calculateSeed();
        }

        // Generates a deterministic seed based on position and depth.
        // This is critical for ensuring the same part of space always generates the same content.
        calculateSeed() {
            // A simple hashing function
            let h1 = 0xdeadbeef, h2 = 0x41c6ce57;
            const s1 = Math.floor(this.x);
            const s2 = Math.floor(this.y);
            const s3 = this.depth;
            h1 = Math.imul(h1 ^ s1, 2654435761);
            h2 = Math.imul(h2 ^ s1, 1597334677);
            h1 = Math.imul(h1 ^ s2, 2654435761);
            h2 = Math.imul(h2 ^ s2, 1597334677);
            h1 = Math.imul(h1 ^ s3, 2654435761);
            h2 = Math.imul(h2 ^ s3, 1597334677);
            return (h1 ^ h2) >>> 0;
        }

        // Applies grammar rules to create children. This is the core of the generation engine.
        populateNode() {
            if (this.isPopulated || this.depth >= MAX_QUADTREE_DEPTH) return;

            const rng = new LCG(this.seed);
            const structure = expandSymbol(this.symbol, rng);

            if (structure) {
                this.children = [];
                const childSize = this.size / 3; // Using 3x3 grid for expansion
                let structureIndex = 0;
                for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
                    for (let j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
                        const childX = this.x + (j - 1) * childSize;
                        const childY = this.y + (i - 1) * childSize;
                        const childSymbol = structure[structureIndex++];
                        this.children.push(new Quadtree(childX, childY, childSize, this.depth + 1, childSymbol));
                    }
                }
            }
            this.isPopulated = true;
        }

        updateAndDraw(ctx, view, frustum) {
            // Frustum culling: Check if this node is visible
            if (this.x + this.size/2 < frustum.x1 || this.x - this.size/2 > frustum.x2 ||
                this.y + this.size/2 < frustum.y1 || this.y - this.size/2 > frustum.y2) {
                return;
            }

            const sizeOnScreen = this.size * view.zoom;

            // LOD and Subdivision Logic: If the node is large enough on screen, subdivide and recurse.
            if (sizeOnScreen > MIN_NODE_SIZE_ON_SCREEN && this.depth < MAX_QUADTREE_DEPTH) {
                if (!this.isPopulated) {
                    this.populateNode();
                }
                if (this.children) {
                    for (const child of this.children) {
                        child.updateAndDraw(ctx, view, frustum);
                    }
                }
            } else {
                // Render this node's content using the appropriate module
                const screenX = (this.x - view.x) * view.zoom + width / 2;
                const screenY = (this.y - view.y) * view.zoom + height / 2;

                // Invoke the correct generative module based on the node's symbol.
                switch(this.symbol) {
                    case 'S':
                        drawStarSystem(ctx, this.seed, screenX, screenY, sizeOnScreen, view.zoom);
                        break;
                    case 'G':
                        drawGalaxy(ctx, this.seed, screenX, screenY, sizeOnScreen, view.zoom);
                        break;
                    case 'N':
                        drawNebula(ctx, this.seed, screenX, screenY, sizeOnScreen, view.zoom);
                        break;
                    // 'E', 'V', 'C', 'U' are non-rendering structural symbols at this level.
                }
            }
        }
    }

    // SECTION 5: MAIN APPLICATION LOOP
    // STRATEGIC JUSTIFICATION: This section ties all components together. It handles the continuous
    // rendering loop, updates the view state, and initiates the drawing process starting from the
    // root of the Quadtree. It is the operational executor for the entire system.

    // The root of our universe. It starts with symbol 'U'.
    const UNIVERSE_SIZE = 1e8;
    const root = new Quadtree(0, 0, UNIVERSE_SIZE, 0, 'U');

    // UI elements
    const zoomLevelUI = document.getElementById('zoom-level');
    const coordsUI = document.getElementById('coords');

    function animate() {
        // Clear canvas
        ctx.fillStyle = '#000000';
        ctx.fillRect(0, 0, width, height);

        // Smooth zooming and panning
        const lerpFactor = 0.1;
        view.zoom += (view.targetZoom - view.zoom) * lerpFactor;
        view.x += (view.targetX - view.x) * lerpFactor;
        view.y += (view.targetY - view.y) * lerpFactor;

        // Define the viewing frustum in world coordinates
        const frustum = {
            x1: view.x - (width / 2) / view.zoom,
            x2: view.x + (width / 2) / view.zoom,
            y1: view.y - (height / 2) / view.zoom,
            y2: view.y + (height / 2) / view.zoom
        };

        // Start the recursive drawing process from the root node
        root.updateAndDraw(ctx, view, frustum);

        // Update UI
        zoomLevelUI.textContent = `Zoom: ${view.zoom.toExponential(2)}`;
        coordsUI.textContent = `Pos: (${Math.round(view.x)}, ${Math.round(view.y)})`;

        requestAnimationFrame(animate);
    }

    // Start the simulation.
    animate();

    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

