subStrategies.solutionAttempt:
### **Strategic Execution Framework**

**1. Sub-strategy Restatement:**
The designated approach is the "Hybrid Observational & Physically-Modeled Realism Approach." This strategy mandates the creation of a cosmic visualization by merging two distinct data sources: a core set of authoritative, discrete astronomical objects (ground-truth data) and a supplementary layer of procedurally generated content (nebulae, faint stars) derived from scientific models. The goal is to achieve high experiential fidelity, creating an immersive and awe-inspiring environment that remains grounded in scientific plausibility.

**2. Execution Plan Outline:**
The implementation will be encapsulated within a single, standalone HTML document. All necessary components—structure (HTML), styling (CSS), and logic (JavaScript, GLSL)—will be self-contained.

*   **Phase 1: Dual-Path Data & Model Development:**
    *   **Path A (Observational Data):** A small, representative mock dataset of "catalogued" stars will be defined directly in the JavaScript code. This dataset will serve as the verifiable ground truth for the simulation, with each star possessing distinct properties (name, position, type).
    *   **Path B (Physically-Modeled Data):**
        *   **Background Stars:** A statistical distribution will be used to generate a large quantity of faint, non-catalogued stars, filling the visual void and enhancing the sense of scale.
        *   **Volumetric Nebula:** A physically-based noise algorithm (a multi-octave 3D Simplex noise) will be implemented in a GLSL fragment shader. This will model the gaseous structure of a nebula.

*   **Phase 2: Composite Rendering Engine Architecture:**
    *   A rendering engine will be constructed using the Three.js library, which provides a high-level API for the WebGL graphics pipeline.
    *   **Particle Renderer:** Both observational and procedural stars will be rendered as `THREE.Points` objects for maximum performance.
    *   **Volumetric Renderer:** The nebula will be rendered using a raymarching algorithm implemented in a custom GLSL shader. This shader will be applied to a `THREE.BoxGeometry` that defines the volume's boundaries.
    *   **Integration:** All visual elements will coexist within a single `THREE.Scene`, sharing a unified coordinate system and a `THREE.PerspectiveCamera`. A visual distinction mechanism will be implemented via a UI control, allowing the user to toggle the visibility of the procedurally generated content, thereby separating observed fact from plausible modeling.

*   **Phase 3: Context-Aware Interaction Design:**
    *   **Navigation:** User interaction will center on mouse controls for orbiting and a velocity-based scrolling mechanism to create a powerful "infinite zoom" effect.
    *   **Data Inquiry:** A raycasting system will be implemented to allow users to click on the "catalogued" stars. A successful intersection will display that star's specific data in a UI panel.
    *   **UI Controls:** A simple, non-intrusive UI will provide a toggle to switch between the pure "observational data" view and the "enhanced realism" view (with procedural content enabled).

*   **Phase 4: Balanced Performance Strategy:**
    *   The primary computational load—rendering thousands of stars and raymarching a volumetric nebula—will be offloaded entirely to the GPU via Three.js and custom shaders.
    *   The raymarching algorithm will use a fixed, reasonable number of steps to balance visual quality with real-time performance on standard hardware.
    *   The nebula's appearance will be animated subtly using a time-based uniform variable in the shader, minimizing CPU overhead.

**3. Knowledge Packet Integration:**
No prior knowledge packet was provided. The execution will proceed based solely on the principles and constraints outlined in the assigned sub-strategy.

**4. Analytical Framework & Terminology:**
The solution will utilize standard terminologies from computer graphics and astronomy.
*   **WebGL:** The low-level browser API for rendering 2D and 3D graphics.
*   **Three.js:** A JavaScript library used to abstract and simplify WebGL development.
*   **GLSL (OpenGL Shading Language):** The language used to write shaders that run on the GPU.
*   **Shader:** A program that runs on the GPU, controlling how geometry is processed (Vertex Shader) and how pixels are colored (Fragment Shader).
*   **Raymarching:** A rendering technique for volumetric effects where a ray is advanced in discrete steps through a volume, accumulating color and density at each step.
*   **Simplex Noise:** A gradient noise algorithm used for procedural texture generation.
*   **Raycasting:** The process of projecting a ray from the camera through the mouse cursor's position to detect intersections with objects in the 3D scene.

---

### **Complete Step-by-Step Execution**

The following code constitutes the complete and definitive solution. It is a single, self-contained HTML file that executes the specified sub-strategy.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Cosmic Void - An Infinite Journey</title>
    <style>
        /* CSS Reset and Basic Setup */
        * {
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            box-sizing: border-box;
        }

        html, body {
            overflow: hidden;
            width: 100%;
            height: 100%;
            background-color: #000000;
            font-family: 'monospace', 'Courier New', Courier;
            color: #ffffff;
        }

        /* WebGL Canvas Styling */
        #webgl-canvas {
            position: fixed;
            top: 0;
            left: 0;
            outline: none;
        }

        /* UI Element Styling for "Cool and Mysterious Vibe" */
        .ui-container {
            position: fixed;
            top: 20px;
            left: 20px;
            z-index: 10;
            pointer-events: none;
            text-shadow: 0 0 5px rgba(0, 191, 255, 0.7);
        }

        h1 {
            font-size: 2em;
            font-weight: normal;
            letter-spacing: 2px;
            color: #d0d0ff;
        }

        p {
            font-size: 0.9em;
            color: #a0a0c0;
        }

        /* Star Information Panel */
        #info-panel {
            position: fixed;
            bottom: 20px;
            left: 20px;
            z-index: 10;
            background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
            border: 1px solid rgba(0, 191, 255, 0.3);
            border-radius: 5px;
            padding: 15px;
            display: none; /* Initially hidden */
            max-width: 300px;
            color: #e0e0ff;
            text-shadow: 0 0 3px rgba(0, 191, 255, 0.5);
        }

        #info-panel h2 {
            margin-bottom: 10px;
            font-size: 1.2em;
            color: #ffffff;
            border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(0, 191, 255, 0.2);
            padding-bottom: 5px;
        }

        #info-panel p {
            margin-bottom: 5px;
            line-height: 1.4;
        }

        /* UI Controls for Realism Toggle */
        .controls-container {
            position: fixed;
            top: 20px;
            right: 20px;
            z-index: 10;
            background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
            border: 1px solid rgba(0, 191, 255, 0.3);
            padding: 10px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            pointer-events: all;
        }

        .controls-container label {
            display: flex;
            align-items: center;
            cursor: pointer;
            font-size: 0.9em;
        }

        .controls-container input[type="checkbox"] {
            margin-right: 10px;
        }

    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="ui-container">
        <h1>Cosmic Void</h1>
        <p>Scroll to zoom, drag to look around.</p>
    </div>

    <div id="info-panel">
        <h2 id="star-name"></h2>
        <p id="star-type"></p>
        <p id="star-coords"></p>
        <p id="star-desc"></p>
    </div>

    <div class="controls-container">
        <label for="realism-toggle">
            <input type="checkbox" id="realism-toggle" checked>
            Enhanced Realism (Procedural)
        </label>
    </div>

    <canvas id="webgl-canvas"></canvas>

    <!--
    SECTION: JAVASCRIPT LIBRARIES
    This section imports the Three.js library from a content delivery network (CDN).
    This is necessary to access the WebGL API through a high-level framework as per the strategy.
    It includes the core library and the OrbitControls add-on for camera manipulation.
    -->
    <script async src="https://unpkg.com/es-module-shims@1.6.3/dist/es-module-shims.js"></script>
    <script type="importmap">
    {
        "imports": {
            "three": "https://unpkg.com/three@0.157.0/build/three.module.js",
            "three/addons/": "https://unpkg.com/three@0.157.0/examples/jsm/"
        }
    }
    </script>

    <!--
    SECTION: CORE APPLICATION LOGIC
    This script contains the entire implementation of the sub-strategy.
    -->
    <script type="module">
